choice.explanation:
Step 1: Identify the pseudo‐Goldstone boson  
Because the tree‐level potential is classically scale‐invariant, there is one flat direction (the “dilaton” or pseudo‐Goldstone of broken scale invariance).  This is our light CP‐even state, \(H_{2}\).

Step 2: One‐loop mass from the Coleman–Weinberg potential  
The leading mass squared of the pseudo‐Goldstone is generated entirely by quantum loops.  In general for a flat direction with vacuum expectation \(v_{0}=\sqrt{v^{2}+x^{2}}\), the one‐loop mass formula is
\[
m_{2}^{2}
=\frac{1}{8\pi^{2}v_{0}^{2}}
\sum_{i}n_{i}M_{i}^{4},
\]
where \(n_{i}\) is the spin–statistics and multiplicity factor (positive for bosons, negative for fermions).

Step 3: List all contributing states  
• SM Higgs \(h_{1}\): \(n=1\)  
• Gauge bosons: \(W\) has \(n=6\), \(Z\) has \(n=3\)  
• New scalars from \(S\): charged \(H^{\pm}\) (n=2), neutral CP‐even \(H^{0}\) (n=1), CP‐odd \(A^{0}\) (n=1)  
• Fermions: top quark \(t\) (Dirac, \(n=-12\)), heavy Majorana neutrinos \(N_{i}\) (\(n=-2\) each)

Step 4: Assemble the formula  
Grouping all bosonic terms with positive coefficients and fermionic terms with negative ones, one finds
\[
M_{h_{2}}^{2}
=\frac{1}{8\pi^{2}(v^{2}+x^{2})}
\Bigl\{ 
\alpha_{1}M_{h_{1}}^{4}
+\alpha_{2}M_{W}^{4}
+\alpha_{3}M_{Z}^{4}
+\alpha_{5}M_{H^{\pm}}^{4}
+\alpha_{6}M_{H^{0}}^{4}
+\alpha_{7}M_{A^{0}}^{4}
-\alpha_{4}M_{t}^{4}
-\alpha_{8}\sum_{i}M_{N_{i}}^{4}
\Bigr\},
\]
exactly matching option B.

ANSWER: B

